{"author":"Joe Oakhart","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Why\n\nInvariant I9 says compaction must stay safe against concurrent remote appends and must\nnever assume the per-clone lock excludes remote writers. The existing regression\n(`test_sub_horizon_append_orphan_recovered_by_fsck_rebuild` in\n`tests/integration/test_concurrency_regression.py`) simulates the interleaving by\ncopying clone B's event file into clone A by hand plus a `--no-verify` commit — it never\ndoes a real push/fetch/merge, so the actual publish/reconverge timing and retry logic\nare unexercised. The report's suggested \"either visible or fsck repairs it\" oracle is\ntoo permissive (a bug forcing every normal append through repair would still pass).\n\n## What\n\n- Add real push/fetch/merge interleaving tests with a tightened, scenario-specific\n  oracle, keeping the existing manual-copy test as the fast deterministic regression.\n\nInjection mechanics (committed, since `compact` holds one flock across an inline\ncritical section with no mid-flock hook): drive A's compaction with `--skip-sync` so the\ntest controls sync timing explicitly, rather than relying on compaction's own\n`_sync_before_compact`. B's real push/fetch/merge is sequenced by the test around A's\n`--skip-sync` compaction, not injected mid-flock.\n\n## Scope\n\n- `tests/integration/test_concurrency_regression.py` (or a sibling integration module)\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Scenario A (normal horizon, real push): A syncs, then compacts with `--skip-sync`;\n      B appends and PUSHES a current-time event during A's compaction window; after A\n      fetches+reconverges, B's event is IMMEDIATELY visible, `fsck` is clean, and NO\n      repair command is required.\n- [ ] Scenario B (adversarial ordering, real push): force A's snapshot to carry a\n      far-future timestamp by running A's `compact` subprocess with `REBAR_HLC_NOW` set\n      to a far-future value, while B appends at a normal clock — so B's event filename\n      prefix is guaranteed to sort BEFORE A's snapshot and is excluded from its\n      `source_event_uuids`. **Sequencing (critical):** B must create+push its event at a\n      normal clock BEFORE it fetches/witnesses A's far-future post-compact HEAD —\n      otherwise B's HLC absorbs the far-future timestamp and B's subsequent event sorts\n      AFTER the snapshot, defeating the adversarial ordering. Assert `fsck`\n      deterministically flags the orphan,\n      `--repair-snapshots` on A restores the exact event, THEN A pushes the repaired\n      commit and B fetches+syncs. Because B never compacted, after fetch B holds BOTH its\n      live `.json` orphan and A's rebuilt snapshot that already folded+retired it — so B\n      must then run `fsck --repair` (mirroring the resurrection pattern in\n      `test_two_clone_compaction_resurrection_no_data_loss_and_repairable`). Assert that\n      after B's repair BOTH clones show identical ticket state with no UUID/content lost.\n- [ ] The existing manual-copy test is retained as a fast Scenario-B regression.\n- [ ] `make lint && make typecheck && make test` pass."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1783898134699467001,"uuid":"8848b2c8-0661-40ce-9f3b-5f98f559a252"}